<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ910626-0062</DOCNO><DOCID>910626-0062.</DOCID><HL>   Tuesday's Markets:   Stocks Decline,   Bonds Advance,   Dollar Is Mixed   ----   By Douglas R. Sease   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal</HL><DATE>06/26/91</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE C1</SO><IN>BOND MARKET NEWS (BON)CDS, INTEREST RATES, COMMERCIAL PAPER (FIN)FOREIGN-EXCHANGE MARKETS (FRX)STOCK INDEXES (NDX)STOCK MARKET, OFFERINGS (STK)U.S. STOCK MARKET STATISTICS (STT)</IN><NS>BOND MARKET NEWS (BON)FOREIGN EXCHANGE (FRX)STOCK AND OTHER INDEXES (NDX)STOCK andamp; OTHER MARKET NEWS (STK)</NS><GV>TREASURY DEPARTMENT (TRE)</GV><RE>NORTH AMERICA (NME)UNITED STATES (US)</RE><LP>   Stock prices continued to slide after Monday's big plunge,while bonds rose and the dollar was mixed.   The Dow Jones Industrial Average lost 2.90 points to closeat 2910.11 in moderately active trading. Analysts said stockprices are in the midst of a correction that is bringing themmore in line with bond yields and expectations forless-than-robust second-quarter profits.</LP><TEXT>   The Dow Jones industrials lost more than 52 points Mondayin a sell-off triggered by a scandal in the Japanesesecurities industry, which also resulted in the resignationof the presidents of two big brokerage firms. The Nikkeiindex plunged more than 2% Monday but closed modestly higheryesterday.   Bank stocks were big losers in the U.S. yesterday afterWells Fargo andamp; Co. said it expected sharply lowersecond-quarter earnings and a large provision for loanlosses.   &quot;The U.S. stock market is being set up for additionaldeclines from here,&quot; said James Solloway, director ofresearch at Argus Research. &quot;We had a big break Monday andonly a half-hearted attempt at a recovery. This is indicativeof a somewhat sick market.&quot;   Even though prices of long-term Treasury bonds inchedhigher, the 8.50% yield on the Treasury's benchmark 30-yearbond is still considered attractive by some analysts. &quot;Bondsare providing stiff competition to stocks,&quot; said Mr.Solloway. &quot;It's hard not to be attracted to an 8.5% yieldwhen inflation is running less than 4%.&quot;   In major market action:                                                                                                          Stock prices fell. Volume on the New York Stock Exchangetotaled 155.5 million shares. Declining issues on the BigBoard were ahead of gainers 887 to 623.                                                                                                          Bond prices edged higher. The Treasury's benchmark 30-yearbond rose less than an eighth of a point, or less than $1.25for each $1,000 face amount. The yield on the issue slippedto 8.50%.                                                                                                          The dollar was mixed. In late New York trading thecurrency was quoted at 1.7935 marks and 138.25 yen, comparedwith 1.7825 marks and 138.71 yen Monday.</TEXT></DOC>